# No Target-Specific Branches

**CRITICAL**: Never *name a target* in target-agnostic code. This covers two forms of the same mistake: **branching** on a `target` value, and embedding **target-named constants, helpers, or data** in framework/core packages. Target-specific logic *and target-specific facts* belong in adapters and target packages.

**❌ WRONG: Branch on target in core packages**

```typescript
function canonicalizeColumnType(scalar: string, target: string): string {
  if (target === 'postgres') {
    const scalarMap: Record<string, string> = {
      int4: 'pg/int4@1',
      text: 'pg/text@1',
    };
    return scalarMap[scalar] ?? scalar;
  }
  return scalar;
}
```

**✅ CORRECT: Put target-specific logic behind an adapter interface**

```typescript
interface Adapter {
  canonicalizeType(scalar: string): string;
}

class PostgresAdapter implements Adapter {
  canonicalizeType(scalar: string): string {
    const scalarMap: Record<string, string> = {
      int4: 'pg/int4@1',
      text: 'pg/text@1',
    };
    return scalarMap[scalar] ?? scalar;
  }
}
```

## Named-target constants and data are the same violation

The branch is the obvious form. The subtler form is a target-agnostic package that *names* a target in a constant, a helper name, or static data — even with no `if` in sight. A `POSTGRES_DEFAULT_NAMESPACE_ID` constant or a `defaultNamespaceIdForSqlTarget()` helper sitting in the framework core is just a branch that has been pre-evaluated: the framework now knows a Postgres-specific fact.

**❌ WRONG: Target-named constant / helper in a target-agnostic package**

```typescript
// in packages/1-framework/** (target-agnostic)
export const POSTGRES_DEFAULT_NAMESPACE_ID = 'public';

export function defaultNamespaceIdForSqlTarget(targetId: string): string {
  return targetId === 'postgres' ? 'public' : '__unbound__';
}
```

**✅ CORRECT: The target declares the fact on its descriptor; the framework reads it generically**

```typescript
// in the target package's descriptor (static data the target owns)
const postgresDescriptorMeta = {
  // …
  defaultNamespaceId: 'public',
};

// in the target-agnostic consumer — reads the fact, never names the target
const defaultNamespaceId = target.defaultNamespaceId;
```

Target-specific *facts* are static target data: they live on the target descriptor, and target-agnostic code consumes them through a uniform field. See [ADR 223 — Target-owned default namespace](../../docs/architecture%20docs/adrs/ADR%20223%20-%20Target-owned%20default%20namespace.md) for the canonical worked example of this distinction (a default namespace is an authoring-time fact the target owns, not a branch the framework evaluates).

## AST class fields are the same violation

The branch-as-`if`, the target-named constant, and the **target-specific field on a generic AST class** are three forms of the same mistake. An optional field on a shared core AST class that exists only because *one* target needs it is just a branch the renderer evaluates per-target — the field name encodes the target's existence into the generic class.

**❌ WRONG: Target-specific field on a generic core AST class**

```typescript
// in packages/2-sql/4-lanes/relational-core (generic SQL core)
export class TableSource extends ExprBase {
  readonly name: string;
  readonly schema?: string; // ← Postgres has schemas; SQLite doesn't. Generic core now knows.
  // …
}
```

The renderer downstream is forced into a per-target branch:

```typescript
// Postgres renderer uses schema
const qualifiedName = source.schema ? `"${source.schema}"."${source.name}"` : `"${source.name}"`;

// SQLite renderer rejects schema
if (source.schema !== undefined) throw new Error('SQLite tables have no schema');
```

Both renderers are now branching on a generic-core field whose presence is a Postgres-only fact. The branch isn't in the core, but the field is — and the field exists *because* of the target distinction.

**✅ CORRECT: Target-contributed AST subclass in the target package**

```typescript
// in packages/2-sql/4-lanes/relational-core (stays generic)
export class TableSource extends ExprBase {
  readonly name: string;
  // …
}

// in packages/3-targets/3-targets/postgres (target-contributed)
export class PostgresTableSource extends TableSource {
  readonly schema?: string;
  // …
}
```

The Postgres renderer reaches `PostgresTableSource` via the same double-dispatch the Slice 1 DDL visitor uses. The SQLite renderer never sees the schema-qualified form because SQLite code doesn't produce it. The generic core stays target-agnostic.

This mirrors the established three-layer polymorphic IR pattern (`packages/2-sql/4-lanes/relational-core/src/ast/ddl-types.ts` defines the family DDL base; `PostgresCreateTable extends DdlNode` lives in the postgres target package, not in core). When a new field is needed and only one target uses it, the right move is *almost always* a target-contributed subclass, never an optional field on the generic base.

## Why this matters

- Keeps the core target-agnostic (“thin core, fat targets”)
- Avoids hard-to-extend `if/else` and `switch` ladders as targets grow
- Improves testability by mocking the adapter interface instead of branching on target
- A target-named constant in the framework is a layer-purity violation that no `if` statement makes visible — naming the target is the tell, with or without a branch
- A target-specific *field* on a generic AST class is a branch the renderer evaluates, just pre-encoded into the class — the field's presence is the layer-purity violation
